1
00:00:02,440 --> 00:00:03,880
Police, please.

2
00:00:06,040 --> 00:00:07,240
(TREMBLING) Hello?

3
00:00:08,920 --> 00:00:10,040
Yes.

4
00:00:11,280 --> 00:00:12,360
I know who did it.

5
00:00:13,600 --> 00:00:15,360
-Who did it all.
-(SOFT HISSING)

6
00:00:15,440 --> 00:00:16,720
I figured it out.

7
00:00:17,880 --> 00:00:19,760
No. No, I can't speak up.

8
00:00:19,840 --> 00:00:21,240
They might hear me.

9
00:00:22,360 --> 00:00:23,360
Oh, no.

10
00:00:23,920 --> 00:00:25,960
-Oh, no. Listen.
-(FAINT RIPPLING)

11
00:00:26,800 --> 00:00:28,080
Listen.

12
00:00:28,760 --> 00:00:29,960
They are everywhere.

13
00:00:31,280 --> 00:00:32,320
All around.

14
00:00:32,400 --> 00:00:33,800
(LOUD BUZZING)

15
00:00:33,880 --> 00:00:35,320
We've been so blind.

16
00:00:35,400 --> 00:00:36,480
(SCREAMS)

17
00:00:44,120 --> 00:00:46,720
WOMAN: (ON PHONE) Hello? Sir?

18
00:00:46,800 --> 00:00:48,680
Are you in a safe place?

19
00:00:49,600 --> 00:00:51,720
Are you being held against your will?

20
00:00:52,320 --> 00:00:53,400
Sir?

21
00:00:54,960 --> 00:00:57,760
(BUZZING)

22
00:01:01,720 --> 00:01:04,480
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

23
00:01:41,880 --> 00:01:43,560
You could leave all that stuff
here, you know.

24
00:01:43,640 --> 00:01:45,240
We do have literally acres of room.

25
00:01:45,320 --> 00:01:48,400
Oh, no. It's all right.
Danny"s got a little bit territorial.

26
00:01:48,480 --> 00:01:51,360
The idea of me leaving
so much as a toothbrush here...

27
00:01:51,440 --> 00:01:53,040
But still, he's all right
with us doing this,

28
00:01:53,120 --> 00:01:54,160
which I admit's a little bit weird.

29
00:01:54,240 --> 00:01:57,040
'Cause you'd think if he had a problem
with me leaving stuff in the Tardis

30
00:01:57,120 --> 00:02:00,120
he'd object to me travelling
in the Tardis but he's not, so...

31
00:02:00,200 --> 00:02:02,120
Sorry, stopped listening a while ago.
Okay.

32
00:02:02,200 --> 00:02:05,840
Uh, same time you left,
same place...ish.

33
00:02:06,640 --> 00:02:07,720
Ish?

34
00:02:08,600 --> 00:02:09,920
Don't give me an "ish".

35
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:13,280
These readings are very, um...

36
00:02:13,360 --> 00:02:14,560
ish-y.

37
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:16,560
(BEEPING)

38
00:02:16,640 --> 00:02:17,640
(PINGING)

39
00:02:19,360 --> 00:02:21,040
(POWER FLUCTUATING)

40
00:02:22,520 --> 00:02:24,640
Um, Doctor?

41
00:02:24,720 --> 00:02:25,720
Uh-huh?

42
00:03:02,640 --> 00:03:04,040
(GRUNTING)

43
00:03:08,760 --> 00:03:09,880
Well...

44
00:03:09,960 --> 00:03:12,440
Well, I wonder what caused this?

45
00:03:14,080 --> 00:03:15,760
I don't think we're bigger, are we?

46
00:03:15,840 --> 00:03:17,600
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

47
00:03:19,600 --> 00:03:21,840
Bristol? Doctor, we're in Bristol!

48
00:03:21,920 --> 00:03:25,080
And 120 miles from where we should be.
Impressive!

49
00:03:25,160 --> 00:03:26,800
No, not impressive, annoying.

50
00:03:26,880 --> 00:03:28,680
No, this is impressive.
This is annoying.

51
00:03:28,960 --> 00:03:31,000
The Tardis never does this.
This is huge!

52
00:03:31,080 --> 00:03:35,400
Well, not literally huge,
slightly smaller than usual,

53
00:03:35,480 --> 00:03:36,720
which is huge.

54
00:03:36,800 --> 00:03:39,280
Yes, I get it. You're excited.
When can I go home?

55
00:03:39,360 --> 00:03:40,920
Your house isn't going anywhere.

56
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:44,360
But then neither is mine
until I get this figured out.

57
00:03:45,160 --> 00:03:49,760
Could you not just let me enjoy
this moment of not knowing something?

58
00:03:49,840 --> 00:03:52,040
I mean, it happens so rarely.

59
00:03:52,760 --> 00:03:55,280
Uh, look.
I don't think this is dangerous

60
00:03:55,360 --> 00:03:57,560
but I wouldn't like you
to get squished accidentally.

61
00:03:57,960 --> 00:04:00,840
Anyway, I need you to help me
find out what's caused this.

62
00:04:00,920 --> 00:04:02,320
Fine.

63
00:04:03,280 --> 00:04:05,000
I'll go and take a look around.

64
00:04:14,160 --> 00:04:18,880
FENTON: It's your filth, Rigsy.
Start with your signature.

65
00:04:26,040 --> 00:04:27,760
Oh, come on, there's no need for this.

66
00:04:29,880 --> 00:04:31,200
FENTON: There you go.

67
00:04:37,280 --> 00:04:38,520
Get on with it.

68
00:04:38,600 --> 00:04:41,440
This is community service,
not a holiday camp.

69
00:04:42,680 --> 00:04:45,280
-(DOCTOR GRUNTS)
-(MACHINE BEEPING)

70
00:04:46,680 --> 00:04:48,640
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

71
00:04:50,080 --> 00:04:52,400
-(THUDDING)
-(ALARM BLARING)

72
00:04:53,240 --> 00:04:54,720
Now, that wasn't me, was it?

73
00:05:04,680 --> 00:05:06,880
Oh, that can't be good.

74
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:23,200
Cheer up, love. Might never happen.

75
00:05:25,040 --> 00:05:27,240
Have some respect. She's grieving.

76
00:05:28,320 --> 00:05:30,760
Oh, sorry, love.
I didn't mean nothing by it.

77
00:05:36,360 --> 00:05:38,840
Sorry about them. They're idiots.

78
00:05:38,920 --> 00:05:41,920
Oh, that's all right, don't worry.
I've heard worse.

79
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:45,000
I've, er, lost someone, too.
My Aunt Karina.

80
00:05:45,480 --> 00:05:46,600
Deaf as a post.

81
00:05:46,680 --> 00:05:48,400
Didn't really know her that well
but she's still gone.

82
00:05:49,840 --> 00:05:52,480
-Is your one in the mural?
-Oh, no. I haven't actually...

83
00:05:52,680 --> 00:05:54,440
I'm sure they'll get around
to it at some point.

84
00:05:55,120 --> 00:05:56,640
I'm not really with that lot out there,

85
00:05:56,720 --> 00:05:58,800
I just have to do this
community service thing.

86
00:05:58,880 --> 00:05:59,920
I just do graffiti.

87
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:02,640
Not anything, you know, murdery or...

88
00:06:02,720 --> 00:06:03,960
(CHUCKLES)

89
00:06:04,560 --> 00:06:06,760
So, um, what's all this about?

90
00:06:08,600 --> 00:06:10,320
What's happened to all these people?

91
00:06:10,400 --> 00:06:11,720
You mean, you don't know?

92
00:06:13,560 --> 00:06:16,000
CLARA: Hey, I think
I've found something.

93
00:06:16,080 --> 00:06:17,520
People are missing all over the estate.

94
00:06:17,600 --> 00:06:19,920
-Do you think there's a connection?
-Could be.

95
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:21,720
And where are you?

96
00:06:21,800 --> 00:06:24,760
-Exactly where I was.
-No, you're not.

97
00:06:24,840 --> 00:06:26,680
I'm here and I can't see...

98
00:06:27,840 --> 00:06:29,280
Oh.

99
00:06:29,360 --> 00:06:31,160
Yes, "oh".

100
00:06:31,680 --> 00:06:33,520
(GIGGLING)

101
00:06:33,600 --> 00:06:35,680
Oh, my God, that is so adorable.
Are you in there?

102
00:06:35,760 --> 00:06:38,320
Yes, I am. And no, it's not adorable.

103
00:06:38,400 --> 00:06:41,720
It's very, very serious.

104
00:06:41,800 --> 00:06:44,280
So, is this more shrink-ray stuff?
Are you tiny in there?

105
00:06:44,360 --> 00:06:45,440
No.

106
00:06:46,920 --> 00:06:48,520
I'm exactly the same size.

107
00:06:48,880 --> 00:06:51,760
It's merely the exterior
dimensions that have changed.

108
00:06:56,480 --> 00:06:57,640
(LAUGHS)

109
00:06:57,720 --> 00:06:59,280
Stop laughing, this is serious.

110
00:06:59,360 --> 00:07:02,360
Well, I can't help it, can I?
With you and your big old face.

111
00:07:03,440 --> 00:07:05,040
-How are you going to get out?
-Well, plainly I can't.

112
00:07:05,120 --> 00:07:07,680
Something nearby is
leeching all the external dimensions.

113
00:07:07,760 --> 00:07:08,920
-Aliens?
-Possibly.

114
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:10,760
Oh, who am I kidding? Probably.

115
00:07:10,840 --> 00:07:13,640
Sensors are down and I can't risk
taking off with it in this state.

116
00:07:13,720 --> 00:07:17,520
Clara, I need you
to pick up the Tardis.

117
00:07:17,600 --> 00:07:19,840
Carefully. It should be possible.

118
00:07:20,240 --> 00:07:21,920
I've adjusted the relative gravity...

119
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:23,600
You mean, you've made it lighter?

120
00:07:24,640 --> 00:07:27,160
Clara, it's always lighter.

121
00:07:27,240 --> 00:07:29,200
If the Tardis were to land
with its true weight,

122
00:07:29,280 --> 00:07:30,680
it would fracture
the surface of the Earth.

123
00:07:30,760 --> 00:07:33,560
CLARA: Yeah, maybe a story
for another time. What now?

124
00:07:33,640 --> 00:07:36,600
I've managed to get a rough fix on
the source of the dimensional leaching.

125
00:07:38,120 --> 00:07:40,400
It's roughly northwest. That way.

126
00:07:41,080 --> 00:07:43,000
Please don't do that.
That's just wrong.

127
00:07:45,720 --> 00:07:46,920
Now, listen!

128
00:07:50,360 --> 00:07:51,640
You're going to need these.

129
00:07:51,720 --> 00:07:53,280
Oh, wow!

130
00:07:53,360 --> 00:07:55,880
This is an honour.
Does this mean I'm you now?

131
00:07:55,960 --> 00:07:59,360
No, it does not!
So don't get any ideas.

132
00:08:00,520 --> 00:08:02,160
(DISTANT SIRENS WAILING)

133
00:08:02,760 --> 00:08:05,160
And listen, stick this in your ear.

134
00:08:08,400 --> 00:08:09,560
-Can you hear me?
-Yeah.

135
00:08:09,640 --> 00:08:11,440
-Ow! What just happened?
-Nanotech.

136
00:08:12,120 --> 00:08:14,520
-Just hacked your optic nerve.
-What does that mean?

137
00:08:14,600 --> 00:08:16,280
I see what you see.

138
00:08:17,560 --> 00:08:19,280
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

139
00:08:21,960 --> 00:08:24,040
-Anything?
-Yes, I'm dizzy.

140
00:08:24,360 --> 00:08:25,560
But nothing useful.

141
00:08:27,360 --> 00:08:29,200
-You never did tell me your name.
-No time to fraternise.

142
00:08:29,280 --> 00:08:30,960
-Come on, get rid of him.
-CLARA: I'm, um...

143
00:08:32,800 --> 00:08:34,960
-I'm the Doctor.
-Don't you dare.

144
00:08:35,040 --> 00:08:37,960
Doctor Oswald. (CLEARS THROAT)
But you can call me Clara.

145
00:08:38,680 --> 00:08:39,720
I'm Rigsy.

146
00:08:39,800 --> 00:08:43,200
-So, uh, what are you a doctor of?
-Of lies.

147
00:08:43,280 --> 00:08:45,320
Well, I'm usually
quite vague about that.

148
00:08:45,400 --> 00:08:47,560
I think I just picked the title
'cause it makes me sound important.

149
00:08:48,120 --> 00:08:50,040
Why, Doctor Oswald, you are hilarious.

150
00:08:50,120 --> 00:08:51,920
Could we get back to work,
do you think?

151
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:53,560
What are you, exactly?
You don't smell like police

152
00:08:53,640 --> 00:08:55,520
but that's some pretty cool gear
you got there.

153
00:08:55,600 --> 00:08:56,720
You like a spy or something?

154
00:08:57,360 --> 00:09:00,440
-Oh, he's a bright one, hang on to him.
-Hmm.

155
00:09:00,520 --> 00:09:02,520
RIGSY: He was the
last one to go missing.

156
00:09:06,600 --> 00:09:09,080
And when he disappeared,
all the doors and windows were locked.

157
00:09:09,520 --> 00:09:10,520
From the inside.

158
00:09:10,600 --> 00:09:13,240
DOCTOR: Oh, now you're talking.
I love a good locked room mystery.

159
00:09:13,320 --> 00:09:15,320
-Yeah, doesn't everyone?
-What?

160
00:09:16,200 --> 00:09:18,680
Huh? Oh, sorry.
I'm talking to somebody else.

161
00:09:18,760 --> 00:09:21,400
He's listening in.
Doctor, Rigsy. Rigsy, Doctor.

162
00:09:21,480 --> 00:09:24,200
-Hello, barely sentient local.
-Another doctor?

163
00:09:24,800 --> 00:09:26,240
How do you sleep at night?

164
00:09:26,320 --> 00:09:30,000
Missing people. Tiny Tardis.
What's the link?

165
00:09:30,080 --> 00:09:32,920
RIGSY: I think this is great that
someone's finally looking into this.

166
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:35,320
The police won't do anything.
They never do on this estate.

167
00:09:35,400 --> 00:09:37,000
People were thinking that...

168
00:09:38,080 --> 00:09:39,360
no one was listening.

169
00:09:40,320 --> 00:09:41,480
That no one cared.

170
00:09:42,120 --> 00:09:43,960
RIGSY: So, yeah. I think
it's great what you're doing.

171
00:09:44,040 --> 00:09:46,080
Clara, look, I think that we can
manage on our own from now on.

172
00:09:46,160 --> 00:09:47,440
Yeah, well, I think
he could still be useful.

173
00:09:47,520 --> 00:09:50,040
He's a pudding brain. Worse than that,
he's a fluorescent pudding brain.

174
00:09:50,120 --> 00:09:51,880
Okay. Fine. And all those
other missing people,

175
00:09:51,960 --> 00:09:53,280
I suppose you know where they lived?

176
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,320
-(WHIRRING)
-He could still be in the room.

177
00:09:56,960 --> 00:09:58,960
-Sorry, what?
-(LAUGHS)

178
00:09:59,040 --> 00:10:01,000
Sorry, nothing.
I was just thinking out loud.

179
00:10:01,080 --> 00:10:03,160
It's like one of those locked room
things you get in books.

180
00:10:03,760 --> 00:10:05,520
It's always something weird, like...

181
00:10:05,600 --> 00:10:07,680
Like he's still in the room
or something.

182
00:10:09,080 --> 00:10:10,160
RIGSY: Do you want to go and
check out another flat?

183
00:10:10,240 --> 00:10:11,760
You know, I think that you were
wrong about this lad.

184
00:10:11,840 --> 00:10:14,360
I think that he could be very useful.
Vital local knowledge.

185
00:10:14,440 --> 00:10:16,680
-Oh, really?
-Yeah, so try not to scare him off.

186
00:10:16,760 --> 00:10:18,320
How would I scare him off?

187
00:10:19,200 --> 00:10:20,800
(SCREEN BUZZING)

188
00:10:21,960 --> 00:10:24,680
Maybe he's lost in
the desert or something.

189
00:10:26,360 --> 00:10:28,960
Okay, right, are we
missing something here?

190
00:10:29,040 --> 00:10:32,000
Missing man. Locked room. Shrink ray.

191
00:10:32,080 --> 00:10:34,560
-Sorry, did you just say shrink ray?
-What if

192
00:10:34,640 --> 00:10:37,600
he is still in this room,
like you said, only tiny?

193
00:10:39,720 --> 00:10:41,320
You know, like,
underneath the sofa or something.

194
00:10:41,400 --> 00:10:43,960
Clara, this is the scaring off
that we were talking about.

195
00:10:44,400 --> 00:10:46,080
(LAUGHING NERVOUSLY) Okay. So, uh..

196
00:10:46,680 --> 00:10:48,320
(STAMMERING) My...
My lunch break's nearly up.

197
00:10:48,400 --> 00:10:50,520
This... This has been, uh...

198
00:10:51,200 --> 00:10:52,400
interesting.

199
00:10:52,480 --> 00:10:54,440
Clara, Local Knowledge is leaving.
Do something!

200
00:10:54,520 --> 00:10:56,600
Rigsy! One sec.

201
00:10:56,960 --> 00:10:58,640
-Doctor, open the doors.
-I didn't mean that!

202
00:10:58,720 --> 00:11:00,960
Look, you want him to stay or not?

203
00:11:01,040 --> 00:11:02,960
-(SIGHS)
-(ELECTRONIC WHIRRING)

204
00:11:03,040 --> 00:11:05,280
You really do throw your companions
in at the deep end, don't you?

205
00:11:06,400 --> 00:11:07,960
Rigsy, come here.

206
00:11:08,040 --> 00:11:09,040
Meet the Doctor.

207
00:11:12,400 --> 00:11:13,400
(CHUCKLES)

208
00:11:14,440 --> 00:11:17,560
-So what do you think, tiny man idea?
-Yes, it's a lovely thought.

209
00:11:17,640 --> 00:11:20,560
Which is why I set the sonic to
scan for that as soon as we entered.

210
00:11:20,640 --> 00:11:22,800
-Pleased to meet you.
-And you didn't think to tell me?

211
00:11:22,880 --> 00:11:24,160
Well, of course he might
have been squashed

212
00:11:24,240 --> 00:11:25,840
under a policeman's shoe by now.

213
00:11:26,280 --> 00:11:28,160
It's bigger. On the inside.

214
00:11:28,240 --> 00:11:30,720
You know, I don't think
that statement's ever been truer.

215
00:11:30,800 --> 00:11:33,600
What are you, like, aliens or something?

216
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:35,000
No.

217
00:11:35,080 --> 00:11:36,320
Well, he is.

218
00:11:37,920 --> 00:11:40,640
-(ALARM BLARING)
-CLARA: Doctor?

219
00:11:40,720 --> 00:11:42,680
-(LOUD HISSING)
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

220
00:11:43,320 --> 00:11:44,600
-Doctor, did you hear that?
-Yes.

221
00:11:44,680 --> 00:11:46,520
Whatever it was, it just drained
a massive amount of energy

222
00:11:46,600 --> 00:11:48,240
from inside the Tardis.

223
00:11:48,320 --> 00:11:50,480
-CLARA: What was it?
-I don't know.

224
00:11:51,480 --> 00:11:53,600
That's the least of my problems,
just get us out of there.

225
00:11:53,680 --> 00:11:56,080
Okay. Go. Rigsy?

226
00:11:56,680 --> 00:11:59,040
This is where we run. Stick with me.

227
00:11:59,120 --> 00:12:00,320
(CLARA GRUNTS)

228
00:12:01,720 --> 00:12:03,920
I mean, this is just embarrassing.

229
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:06,280
I'm from the race that built the Tardis.

230
00:12:06,360 --> 00:12:08,400
Dimensions are kind of our thing.

231
00:12:08,880 --> 00:12:10,600
So why can't I understand this?

232
00:12:11,080 --> 00:12:13,360
Clara, I need more info.

233
00:12:13,440 --> 00:12:15,720
Where else have people disappeared?

234
00:12:16,080 --> 00:12:19,920
-MI5?
-Yes, this case has got our attention.

235
00:12:21,120 --> 00:12:22,840
Well, you've come to
the right place, ma'am.

236
00:12:23,280 --> 00:12:25,680
First reported disappearance,
a Mr Heath.

237
00:12:25,760 --> 00:12:28,480
It's not on the estate but it's
exactly the same MO as the rest.

238
00:12:28,560 --> 00:12:31,800
Clara, I think that your
shrink ray theory was wrong.

239
00:12:31,880 --> 00:12:32,880
My shrink ray theory?

240
00:12:32,960 --> 00:12:35,040
I thought you were
already scanning for that.

241
00:12:35,680 --> 00:12:37,120
Doctor, what are you doing?

242
00:12:37,200 --> 00:12:39,600
Well, it just struck me.
Locked room mysteries.

243
00:12:39,680 --> 00:12:41,880
Classic solution number one,
they're still in the room.

244
00:12:41,960 --> 00:12:44,520
Classic solution number two,
they're in the walls.

245
00:12:44,600 --> 00:12:46,360
What do you mean, they're in the...

246
00:12:46,440 --> 00:12:48,800
PC FORREST: Have we done
as much as we could? No.

247
00:12:49,280 --> 00:12:51,120
Do we have any suspects? No.

248
00:12:51,680 --> 00:12:55,360
Off the record, I think the top
brass are hoping if they ignore this,

249
00:12:55,440 --> 00:12:57,320
it'll all just go away.

250
00:13:00,720 --> 00:13:02,520
Apparently, they're in the walls.

251
00:13:03,280 --> 00:13:05,240
-(RIGSY GRUNTING
-(MOBILE RINGING)

252
00:13:06,600 --> 00:13:08,000
PC Forrest.

253
00:13:08,800 --> 00:13:11,200
Yes, sir. MI5, sir.

254
00:13:11,960 --> 00:13:14,800
So, you and that bloke in a box.
Do you do this sort of stuff a lot?

255
00:13:14,880 --> 00:13:17,640
Oh, well, he's usually
out of the box but yeah.

256
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:19,920
I don't know.

257
00:13:22,680 --> 00:13:25,320
Maybe they thought
we weren't doing enough, sir.

258
00:13:28,760 --> 00:13:31,200
(FAINT RIPPLING)

259
00:13:35,760 --> 00:13:37,600
Can I call you back?

260
00:13:43,720 --> 00:13:45,080
RIGSY: So how'd you get this gig?

261
00:13:45,160 --> 00:13:47,160
Did you, like, study science
or aliens or something?

262
00:13:47,240 --> 00:13:49,120
(LAUGHING) No.

263
00:13:49,200 --> 00:13:51,240
Well, it's kind of
more of a right place, right time

264
00:13:51,320 --> 00:13:53,400
or wrong place, wrong time,
depending on how he's behaving.

265
00:13:53,480 --> 00:13:54,960
DOCTOR:
I can hear you, you know.

266
00:14:00,640 --> 00:14:02,440
(RIPPLING)

267
00:14:02,520 --> 00:14:05,200
PC FORREST: Ma'am?
There's something in here, I think.

268
00:14:08,040 --> 00:14:10,560
(SCREAMING)

269
00:14:12,720 --> 00:14:14,240
(SCREAMING CONTINUES)

270
00:14:17,280 --> 00:14:18,760
PC Forrest?

271
00:14:25,520 --> 00:14:26,640
Hello?

272
00:14:30,560 --> 00:14:31,640
Hello?

273
00:14:34,120 --> 00:14:35,400
Doctor, she's gone.

274
00:14:36,200 --> 00:14:37,400
What am I missing?

275
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:42,280
The Tardis should be able to detect
anything in the known universe.

276
00:14:44,240 --> 00:14:45,360
The known universe.

277
00:14:50,560 --> 00:14:51,640
This universe.

278
00:14:53,320 --> 00:14:54,560
Clara, wait, go back.

279
00:14:54,640 --> 00:14:56,040
Back, back back! That mural.

280
00:15:01,520 --> 00:15:03,960
That is a nervous system.

281
00:15:04,040 --> 00:15:06,040
Scaled up and flattened.

282
00:15:06,120 --> 00:15:09,160
I think we've found PC Forrest.
What's left of her, at least.

283
00:15:09,240 --> 00:15:10,520
Her nervous system?

284
00:15:13,520 --> 00:15:14,840
The mural in the flat.

285
00:15:15,720 --> 00:15:17,040
That wasn't a desert at all.

286
00:15:17,760 --> 00:15:19,960
It's a microscopic blow-up
of human skin.

287
00:15:20,040 --> 00:15:21,120
What?

288
00:15:22,040 --> 00:15:23,960
-Why?
-Whatever they are,

289
00:15:24,040 --> 00:15:26,280
they are... They are experimenting.

290
00:15:26,360 --> 00:15:28,600
They're testing. They are...
They are dissecting.

291
00:15:28,680 --> 00:15:30,040
Trying to understand us.

292
00:15:30,120 --> 00:15:32,640
Trying to understand...three dimensions!

293
00:15:33,600 --> 00:15:34,760
(HISSING)

294
00:15:37,400 --> 00:15:39,560
Ahh! The handle.

295
00:15:39,640 --> 00:15:42,960
Doctor, the handle.
They've flattened the handle.

296
00:15:44,160 --> 00:15:46,760
Fascinating!
Clara, they're in the walls!

297
00:15:46,840 --> 00:15:48,040
(RIPPLING)

298
00:15:48,120 --> 00:15:50,680
Keep away from them,
if they touch you, you're finished.

299
00:15:57,680 --> 00:15:59,600
What happens if they touch us?

300
00:15:59,680 --> 00:16:02,280
-(HISSING)
-I really don't want to find out.

301
00:16:06,720 --> 00:16:08,920
-They can't jump, can they?
-(MOBILE RINGING)

302
00:16:15,160 --> 00:16:16,240
(CLEARS THROAT)

303
00:16:16,320 --> 00:16:17,360
Hey, you!

304
00:16:17,440 --> 00:16:19,480
I've got our bench.
Did you get held up?

305
00:16:19,560 --> 00:16:21,440
Um... Just a little.

306
00:16:21,520 --> 00:16:24,240
Sorry, Danny.
I think lunch is, um, a bust.

307
00:16:24,320 --> 00:16:27,600
Oh, hon, you're missing some
classic park action.

308
00:16:27,680 --> 00:16:28,920
Clara, the window!

309
00:16:29,320 --> 00:16:32,040
Look! Look! They're climbing the walls!

310
00:16:32,120 --> 00:16:34,280
-(LOUD BUZZING)
-DANNY: Who was that?

311
00:16:34,760 --> 00:16:39,040
Um, that's just a guy on community
support and I'm helping him...

312
00:16:39,120 --> 00:16:40,120
find his auntie.

313
00:16:40,200 --> 00:16:41,920
Nice. Not technically lying.

314
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:45,120
-(CLARA PANTING)
-Sounds, um, kind of active.

315
00:16:45,200 --> 00:16:47,160
Um, yeah.

316
00:16:47,240 --> 00:16:49,880
Um, there was a thing, um, a thing...

317
00:16:49,960 --> 00:16:51,880
Where are you and are you in trouble?

318
00:16:51,960 --> 00:16:54,480
Uh... No, no, no. I'm fine!

319
00:16:56,160 --> 00:16:57,440
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

320
00:16:57,520 --> 00:16:59,320
-(LOUD CRASHING)
-Clara?

321
00:16:59,400 --> 00:17:00,800
(CLARA AND RIGSY SCREAMING)

322
00:17:00,880 --> 00:17:02,160
-Clara?
-(GLASS BREAKING)

323
00:17:02,240 --> 00:17:03,640
-Danny?
-(CAR ALARM BLARING)

324
00:17:03,720 --> 00:17:06,320
-What's happening?
-Uh, er, not much.

325
00:17:06,400 --> 00:17:08,040
Just some nonsense.

326
00:17:10,200 --> 00:17:12,000
-Long story.
-What story?

327
00:17:12,080 --> 00:17:13,960
Uh, tell you later. Love you!

328
00:17:16,200 --> 00:17:17,720
This explains everything.

329
00:17:19,120 --> 00:17:21,040
They're from a universe

330
00:17:21,120 --> 00:17:23,240
with only two dimensions.

331
00:17:23,320 --> 00:17:25,560
And yes, that is a thing!

332
00:17:25,640 --> 00:17:27,400
It's long been theorised, of course,

333
00:17:27,480 --> 00:17:30,760
but no one could go there and prove
its existence without a heck of a diet.

334
00:17:32,040 --> 00:17:34,960
And what long story
are you going to tell Danny, huh?

335
00:17:35,040 --> 00:17:37,080
-Or haven't you made it up yet?
-Sorry, what? What was that?

336
00:17:37,520 --> 00:17:39,360
Excellent lying, Dr Oswald.

337
00:17:39,440 --> 00:17:40,560
Yeah?

338
00:17:40,640 --> 00:17:42,120
Well, I thought
it was pretty weak myself.

339
00:17:42,200 --> 00:17:43,840
I meant to me.

340
00:17:43,920 --> 00:17:47,560
You told me that Danny was okay with
you being back on board the Tardis.

341
00:17:47,640 --> 00:17:48,840
Well, he is.

342
00:17:48,920 --> 00:17:50,280
Yeah, because he doesn't
know anything about it.

343
00:17:50,360 --> 00:17:51,720
-Doctor...
-Congratulations.

344
00:17:51,800 --> 00:17:54,280
-Lying is a vital survival skill.
-Well, there you go.

345
00:17:54,920 --> 00:17:56,880
And a terrible habit.

346
00:17:56,960 --> 00:17:59,560
-(FEEDBACK SCREECHING)
-Doctor, you're breaking up a bit.

347
00:17:59,640 --> 00:18:00,680
(DISTORTED) Yeah, of course I am.

348
00:18:00,760 --> 00:18:02,160
No, really, you are, I can't hear you.

349
00:18:02,800 --> 00:18:04,000
What?

350
00:18:05,160 --> 00:18:08,160
Oh, right, blowing out that window's
possibly affected the earpiece.

351
00:18:08,240 --> 00:18:10,840
-Take it out and sonic it.
-Doing it.

352
00:18:13,680 --> 00:18:14,800
Hey!

353
00:18:15,280 --> 00:18:16,720
They can't do that. Hey!

354
00:18:17,160 --> 00:18:19,240
-What are you doing?
-Our job.

355
00:18:19,800 --> 00:18:22,400
You're on report, by the way.
Late back from lunch.

356
00:18:22,480 --> 00:18:25,640
Does it even still count as lying if
you're doing it for somebody's own good?

357
00:18:25,720 --> 00:18:29,000
-Well, like, technically their own good.
-(WHIRRING)

358
00:18:29,080 --> 00:18:30,080
(BLOWS)

359
00:18:30,160 --> 00:18:31,440
It's a memorial!

360
00:18:31,520 --> 00:18:34,960
Council didn't approve it,
it's graffiti. Stan?

361
00:18:35,840 --> 00:18:37,200
(RIGSY GRUNTING)

362
00:18:37,920 --> 00:18:38,960
Oh.

363
00:18:40,280 --> 00:18:42,560
Look, Clara. Talk to me! Talk to me!

364
00:18:42,640 --> 00:18:44,240
RIGSY:
What are you doing?

365
00:18:46,080 --> 00:18:47,400
(WHIRRING CONTINUES)

366
00:18:48,200 --> 00:18:50,600
Clara, the mural!
Clara, it's the mural!

367
00:18:50,680 --> 00:18:52,560
Over there! Look! The mural!

368
00:18:52,640 --> 00:18:56,120
We've found the missing people.
They're in the walls!

369
00:19:00,120 --> 00:19:02,000
-What do I do?
-Act normal.

370
00:19:02,080 --> 00:19:03,280
But get everyone out.

371
00:19:03,360 --> 00:19:05,800
They're very realistic.
Who painted them?

372
00:19:05,880 --> 00:19:08,680
RIGSY: I don't know. A local artist.
Probably a grieving relative.

373
00:19:08,760 --> 00:19:09,840
CLARA:
Did you ever meet them?

374
00:19:09,920 --> 00:19:14,040
Or did they just appear after
people disappeared?

375
00:19:14,440 --> 00:19:16,880
And who are you
when you're at home, love?

376
00:19:17,920 --> 00:19:20,200
Health & Safety. This subway is unsafe.

377
00:19:20,280 --> 00:19:21,720
Everyone needs to leave right now.

378
00:19:23,600 --> 00:19:26,240
This is blank. Try again, sweetheart.

379
00:19:27,320 --> 00:19:28,840
BOTH: What?

380
00:19:29,560 --> 00:19:32,160
It takes quite a lack of imagination
to beat psychic paper.

381
00:19:32,240 --> 00:19:34,120
Stan, do your job.

382
00:19:34,200 --> 00:19:35,280
Clara, stop him!

383
00:19:35,360 --> 00:19:36,920
(STAN YELLS)

384
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:39,400
-GEORGE: Stan!
-(RIPPLING)

385
00:19:43,920 --> 00:19:46,760
What is this? What are they?

386
00:19:47,760 --> 00:19:50,240
DOCTOR: They're wearing the dead
like camouflage.

387
00:19:52,200 --> 00:19:54,440
CLARA: Forget Stan. Your friend's gone.

388
00:19:54,520 --> 00:19:56,200
Clara, get them out of there!

389
00:19:57,360 --> 00:20:00,000
We need to move. Now.

390
00:20:00,920 --> 00:20:04,080
(LOUD BUZZING AND RIPPLING)

391
00:20:16,360 --> 00:20:18,920
Did they follow us?
'Cause I didn't see them follow us.

392
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:20,400
Are we safe?

393
00:20:20,480 --> 00:20:22,080
Are we really hiding
from killer graffiti?

394
00:20:22,160 --> 00:20:23,280
Oh, this is insane.

395
00:20:23,360 --> 00:20:26,800
I agree. We'll have to think of
a better name for them than that.

396
00:20:26,880 --> 00:20:29,560
I mean, Stan was one of them.
Flattened, dead.

397
00:20:29,640 --> 00:20:32,840
-But coming after us.
-Clara, this is a vital stage.

398
00:20:32,920 --> 00:20:35,120
This little group is currently
confused and disorientated

399
00:20:35,200 --> 00:20:37,360
but pretty soon,
a leader is going to emerge.

400
00:20:37,440 --> 00:20:39,680
You need to make sure
that leader is you.

401
00:20:39,760 --> 00:20:40,840
I'm on it.

402
00:20:40,920 --> 00:20:44,440
George! George, isn't it?
Can you watch that area?

403
00:20:44,520 --> 00:20:46,600
You hear anything, anything moves,
you shout, okay?

404
00:20:46,680 --> 00:20:49,680
He will do no such thing
till I get some answers.

405
00:20:49,760 --> 00:20:52,640
Who are you?
That's what I want to know.

406
00:20:52,720 --> 00:20:56,040
Impersonating a government official.
Trespassing on council property.

407
00:20:56,120 --> 00:20:57,360
-Seriously?
-Seriously.

408
00:20:57,440 --> 00:20:58,480
Fine.

409
00:20:58,560 --> 00:21:00,560
I'll tell you who I am.

410
00:21:01,680 --> 00:21:04,040
I am the one chance you've got
of staying alive.

411
00:21:05,200 --> 00:21:06,280
That's who I am.

412
00:21:07,560 --> 00:21:08,680
Well done.

413
00:21:13,480 --> 00:21:15,680
Rigsy, how well do you know this area?

414
00:21:15,760 --> 00:21:17,000
Do you know where that door leads?

415
00:21:17,080 --> 00:21:19,160
It's the old Brunswick line.
But it's not safe.

416
00:21:19,240 --> 00:21:20,920
Yeah, well, there's safe
and there's safe.

417
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:22,720
Yeah, I know it. I used to
go down there all the time.

418
00:21:22,800 --> 00:21:23,920
Yeah, I'll bet you did.

419
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:26,240
-Painting your filth.
-Yeah, well, you might be glad he did.

420
00:21:26,320 --> 00:21:29,440
Those things come in here,
that is our only way out.

421
00:21:32,080 --> 00:21:33,800
I just hope I can keep them all alive.

422
00:21:33,880 --> 00:21:37,880
Ha, welcome to my world.
So what's next, Doctor Clara?

423
00:21:38,880 --> 00:21:40,480
-Lie to them.
-What?

424
00:21:40,560 --> 00:21:42,000
Lie to them.

425
00:21:42,080 --> 00:21:44,040
Give them hope.
Tell them they're all going to be fine.

426
00:21:44,120 --> 00:21:47,360
-Isn't that what you would do?
-In a manner of speaking.

427
00:21:47,440 --> 00:21:50,040
It's true that people with hope
tend to run faster,

428
00:21:50,120 --> 00:21:51,560
whereas people
who think they're doomed...

429
00:21:51,640 --> 00:21:53,800
Dawdle. End up dead.

430
00:21:54,560 --> 00:21:55,880
So that's what I sound like?

431
00:21:55,960 --> 00:21:57,960
Who's she talking to?

432
00:21:58,040 --> 00:21:59,320
He says it's MI5.

433
00:21:59,400 --> 00:22:00,560
Right, here's something
that might help you.

434
00:22:00,640 --> 00:22:02,480
Do you remember the graffiti
from the estate?

435
00:22:02,560 --> 00:22:04,360
Footprints? Tyre treads?

436
00:22:04,440 --> 00:22:06,240
-Vaguely.
-Well, I don't think it was graffiti.

437
00:22:06,320 --> 00:22:08,800
I think that
that is how those creatures saw us.

438
00:22:08,880 --> 00:22:11,080
The impressions we make
in two-dimensional space.

439
00:22:11,160 --> 00:22:13,880
That was them reaching out,
attempting to talk.

440
00:22:13,960 --> 00:22:17,120
At which point, they moved into
flattening and dissection.

441
00:22:17,200 --> 00:22:20,080
Trying to understand.
Trying to emulate.

442
00:22:20,160 --> 00:22:22,320
But here's the big question.

443
00:22:22,400 --> 00:22:23,960
Do they know they're hurting us?

444
00:22:24,040 --> 00:22:26,360
So, what, you think this is all
one big misunderstanding?

445
00:22:26,440 --> 00:22:29,840
That's a very good question.
Why don't we ask them?

446
00:22:32,720 --> 00:22:34,680
(FEEDBACK WHINING)

447
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:38,760
DOCTOR: We need to find
a way to communicate.

448
00:22:38,840 --> 00:22:40,320
Why can't the Tardis just translate?

449
00:22:40,400 --> 00:22:43,800
Because their idea of language
is just as bizarre

450
00:22:43,880 --> 00:22:46,520
as their idea of space.

451
00:22:46,600 --> 00:22:48,480
Even the Tardis is confused.

452
00:22:48,560 --> 00:22:50,640
FENTON: This is a bad idea.

453
00:22:50,720 --> 00:22:54,400
What makes this colleague of yours
think those monsters even want to talk?

454
00:22:54,480 --> 00:23:00,120
I know a race made of sentient gas
who throw fireballs as a friendly wave.

455
00:23:01,880 --> 00:23:04,880
I know another race with 64 stomachs

456
00:23:04,960 --> 00:23:07,560
who talk to each other
by disembowelling.

457
00:23:07,640 --> 00:23:09,360
-He's got a hunch.
-My point being

458
00:23:09,440 --> 00:23:12,320
that in a universe as immense
and bizarre as this one,

459
00:23:12,400 --> 00:23:14,040
you cannot be too quick to judge.

460
00:23:14,120 --> 00:23:16,200
Perhaps these creatures
don't even understand

461
00:23:16,280 --> 00:23:19,640
that we need
three dimensions to live in.

462
00:23:19,720 --> 00:23:22,880
(GRUNTS) They may not even know
that they're hurting us.

463
00:23:22,960 --> 00:23:25,480
-Do you really believe that?
-No. I really hope that.

464
00:23:25,560 --> 00:23:27,640
Would have made a nice change,
wouldn't it?

465
00:23:28,600 --> 00:23:29,600
Okay.

466
00:23:30,200 --> 00:23:31,600
Let's start with pi.

467
00:23:31,680 --> 00:23:33,680
Even in a flat world,
they would have circles.

468
00:23:33,760 --> 00:23:36,880
I don't mean edible pie,
I mean circular pi.

469
00:23:37,920 --> 00:23:40,880
Which I realise would also
mean edible pie but anyway.

470
00:23:43,720 --> 00:23:45,560
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BEEPING)

471
00:23:45,640 --> 00:23:47,840
(WARBLING THROUGH SPEAKER)

472
00:23:49,640 --> 00:23:51,480
They're responding.

473
00:23:51,760 --> 00:23:53,920
The Tardis is translating now.
It's a number.

474
00:23:54,960 --> 00:23:57,360
-Fifty-five.
-Fifty-five?

475
00:23:57,920 --> 00:23:59,720
-What does that mean?
-Tenth Fibonacci number.

476
00:23:59,800 --> 00:24:01,920
-Atomic number of caesium.
-RIGSY: I know what it means.

477
00:24:02,560 --> 00:24:05,160
We all have numbers on our jackets.
Have to sign them out.

478
00:24:05,240 --> 00:24:08,000
That was the number on Stan's jacket,
the man they found in the subway.

479
00:24:08,080 --> 00:24:10,040
-They're gloating.
-We don't know that.

480
00:24:10,120 --> 00:24:12,240
I mean, it could be an apology,
for all we know.

481
00:24:12,320 --> 00:24:13,720
GEORGE: Really? That's nice of them.

482
00:24:13,800 --> 00:24:15,640
-An apology? Are you seriously...
-(CHITTERING ON SPEAKER)

483
00:24:15,720 --> 00:24:18,480
-Shh, shh, shh. Listen.
-(CHITTERING CONTINUES)

484
00:24:19,280 --> 00:24:20,520
Wait.

485
00:24:21,640 --> 00:24:22,960
DOCTOR: Two-two. 22.

486
00:24:23,520 --> 00:24:25,040
Twenty-two.

487
00:24:25,640 --> 00:24:27,160
That's George.

488
00:24:33,840 --> 00:24:36,520
Looks like your number's up, George.

489
00:24:37,120 --> 00:24:39,160
-Now they're threatening.
-Maybe.

490
00:24:39,240 --> 00:24:41,480
Or maybe they're showing us
they can read.

491
00:24:41,560 --> 00:24:44,000
Oh, grow up. They're picking targets.

492
00:24:44,080 --> 00:24:46,400
-Of course you'd see it that way.
-What do you mean by that?

493
00:24:46,480 --> 00:24:48,400
-CLARA: George?
-Everyone's out to get you, aren't they?

494
00:24:48,480 --> 00:24:50,880
-Well, in this case, they kind of are.
-(SCOFFS)

495
00:24:52,160 --> 00:24:53,600
Clara, be careful.

496
00:24:58,600 --> 00:25:00,280
(RIPPLING)

497
00:25:07,600 --> 00:25:08,920
The tunnel!

498
00:25:12,840 --> 00:25:14,200
CLARA: (PANTING)
Doctor, they've got George.

499
00:25:14,280 --> 00:25:16,480
-I know. I did see.
-What now?

500
00:25:16,560 --> 00:25:19,480
Give me a minute. I'm working on it.

501
00:25:23,400 --> 00:25:25,760
Another flat handle.

502
00:25:26,280 --> 00:25:27,720
They were here.

503
00:25:28,920 --> 00:25:30,920
Not now.

504
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:32,840
They've stopped chasing us, I think.

505
00:25:32,920 --> 00:25:35,400
-It feels like they're cornering us.
-You can't apply human logic.

506
00:25:35,480 --> 00:25:37,440
You're dealing with creatures
from another dimension.

507
00:25:37,520 --> 00:25:40,400
That's three exits
all blocked by those creatures.

508
00:25:40,960 --> 00:25:43,160
Rigsy, where's the next exit?

509
00:25:43,240 --> 00:25:46,120
The only other one I can think of
is where the old line joins the new.

510
00:25:46,200 --> 00:25:48,600
But it's a fair walk. Getting through
that door would be quicker.

511
00:25:48,680 --> 00:25:51,200
-But we can't, can we?
-I'm just saying.

512
00:25:51,840 --> 00:25:53,760
Clara, I might be able to help
with that door.

513
00:25:53,840 --> 00:25:54,960
Give me five minutes.

514
00:26:02,200 --> 00:26:04,440
It's one of mine. Do you like it?

515
00:26:04,520 --> 00:26:06,160
Yeah. Not bad.

516
00:26:07,040 --> 00:26:08,320
So, this thing
that you've been working on?

517
00:26:08,400 --> 00:26:10,760
I think I've figured out a way
to restore three dimensions.

518
00:26:10,840 --> 00:26:13,120
At least on a small scale,
say a door handle.

519
00:26:13,200 --> 00:26:15,400
So what's that, then? A de-flattener?

520
00:26:15,480 --> 00:26:17,400
We're not calling it a de-flattener.

521
00:26:17,480 --> 00:26:20,240
This should be able to
restore dimensions.

522
00:26:20,320 --> 00:26:22,680
-You see what I called it?
-"2-D-is."

523
00:26:22,760 --> 00:26:24,920
-"Two-dee-iss"?
-No, "two-diss"!

524
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:26,680
It's called the 2Dis!

525
00:26:27,800 --> 00:26:29,880
Why do I even bother?
Well, give it a go, then.

526
00:26:32,960 --> 00:26:34,840
(PULSATING)

527
00:26:40,800 --> 00:26:41,920
Hmm.

528
00:26:42,760 --> 00:26:44,440
Long way round it is.

529
00:26:44,520 --> 00:26:47,160
-(MACHINERY HUMMING)
-(ALARM BLARING)

530
00:26:48,120 --> 00:26:49,880
Clara, I don't know how
but they're doing it again,

531
00:26:49,960 --> 00:26:51,280
they're leaching the Tardis!

532
00:26:51,360 --> 00:26:53,160
How? Your doors are closed.

533
00:26:53,800 --> 00:26:56,800
They've changed frequency.
This time it's different.

534
00:26:56,880 --> 00:26:59,080
Listen! The Doctor thinks
we might be in trouble.

535
00:26:59,160 --> 00:27:00,320
He thinks they might be close.

536
00:27:00,400 --> 00:27:02,320
-Where, exactly?
-I don't know. He's not sure.

537
00:27:02,400 --> 00:27:03,720
He's getting readings all around.

538
00:27:03,800 --> 00:27:05,080
Oh, well, that's just great.

539
00:27:05,160 --> 00:27:07,640
Sounds important
but means absolutely nothing.

540
00:27:07,720 --> 00:27:09,000
Can you tell your friend...

541
00:27:09,080 --> 00:27:10,960
(SCREAMING)

542
00:27:17,080 --> 00:27:19,400
Of course. The next stage.

543
00:27:20,160 --> 00:27:21,160
3D!

544
00:27:21,760 --> 00:27:23,720
(RIPPLING)

545
00:27:28,680 --> 00:27:30,160
RIGSY: Run!

546
00:27:34,240 --> 00:27:36,120
Doctor? The door.
The handle's flattened.

547
00:27:36,680 --> 00:27:37,960
I've boosted the output.

548
00:27:38,040 --> 00:27:40,920
-And it will work this time?
-Absolutely.

549
00:27:41,800 --> 00:27:43,520
(PULSATING)

550
00:27:51,680 --> 00:27:54,480
Clara, stop! Use it again.
It can reverse the process.

551
00:27:54,560 --> 00:27:55,960
RIGSY:
There's a ladder at the end of this.

552
00:27:56,040 --> 00:27:57,800
We get down into the tunnel,
we can make it into daylight.

553
00:27:57,880 --> 00:28:00,600
-Hang on! Hang on...
-(PULSATING)

554
00:28:02,760 --> 00:28:04,720
FENTON: If it's flat,
we're safe now, aren't we?

555
00:28:04,840 --> 00:28:06,320
RIGSY: They can't get
through, can they?

556
00:28:06,400 --> 00:28:07,960
Wait.

557
00:28:08,880 --> 00:28:10,400
(CRACKLING)

558
00:28:16,480 --> 00:28:18,080
They have a new ability.

559
00:28:18,160 --> 00:28:19,800
Of course they have.

560
00:28:19,880 --> 00:28:22,360
Now they're 3D,
they can restore dimensions.

561
00:28:26,480 --> 00:28:28,880
Clara, do you want the
good news or the bad news?

562
00:28:28,960 --> 00:28:31,880
(SHOUTING) We're in the bad news!
I'm living the bad news!

563
00:28:31,960 --> 00:28:34,560
The good news is I've come up with
a theoretical way to send them

564
00:28:34,640 --> 00:28:36,720
-back to their own dimension.
-Do it! Now!

565
00:28:36,800 --> 00:28:38,160
That's the bad news.

566
00:28:38,240 --> 00:28:40,600
The Tardis doesn't have enough
dimensional energy to pull it off.

567
00:28:40,680 --> 00:28:42,360
Great. What do you want
me to do about it?

568
00:28:42,440 --> 00:28:44,000
Well, apparently,
these things can now pump it out

569
00:28:44,080 --> 00:28:45,360
as fast as they can steal it.

570
00:28:45,440 --> 00:28:48,040
Maybe if I ask them really nicely,
they'll fill you up again. Hey!

571
00:28:48,120 --> 00:28:50,200
-Give me that machine! Hand it over!
-Doctor!

572
00:28:53,280 --> 00:28:55,160
(ALARMS BLARING)

573
00:28:59,280 --> 00:29:02,000
Hello? Doctor?

574
00:29:02,080 --> 00:29:04,520
Look, can we please
deal with this later?

575
00:29:04,600 --> 00:29:05,760
Because we need to move.

576
00:29:05,840 --> 00:29:07,640
(RIPPLING)

577
00:29:09,960 --> 00:29:12,600
Doctor! Doctor,
I dropped you down a hole.

578
00:29:12,680 --> 00:29:14,040
-Where are you?
-I don't know.

579
00:29:15,760 --> 00:29:17,280
(FLICKING SWITCHES)

580
00:29:17,360 --> 00:29:19,040
My shields have gone!

581
00:29:19,520 --> 00:29:21,320
Structural integrity is failing.

582
00:29:22,080 --> 00:29:23,800
Another blow like that and I've had it.

583
00:29:28,040 --> 00:29:29,560
Uh...

584
00:29:29,640 --> 00:29:30,960
I'm on the train lines.

585
00:29:32,520 --> 00:29:35,800
And there's a train coming.
Of course there is.

586
00:29:37,840 --> 00:29:40,280
Short-term rematerialisation?
Not enough power.

587
00:29:40,360 --> 00:29:41,840
Teleport? Not enough power.

588
00:29:41,920 --> 00:29:43,280
Re-route the heart
of the Tardis through...

589
00:29:43,360 --> 00:29:44,600
Not enough power! Not enough power!

590
00:29:45,240 --> 00:29:46,800
(WHISTLE BLOWING)

591
00:29:47,040 --> 00:29:50,280
-Look, can't you move the Tardis?
-Clara, there is no power.

592
00:29:50,360 --> 00:29:51,880
The Tardis couldn't
boil an egg at the moment.

593
00:29:51,960 --> 00:29:53,880
Listen, do what you can
to get those people out of there.

594
00:29:53,960 --> 00:29:55,280
You're stronger than you know.

595
00:29:55,360 --> 00:29:56,560
I wonder what they're like with ladders?

596
00:29:56,640 --> 00:30:00,440
No, I mean you, move the Tardis.
Like, Addams Family.

597
00:30:19,920 --> 00:30:22,160
(DOCTOR STRAINING)

598
00:30:23,440 --> 00:30:25,200
(TRAIN ENGINE ROARING)

599
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:28,800
(DOCTOR GRUNTING)

600
00:30:33,320 --> 00:30:35,320
Ha! (SCATTING)

601
00:30:36,560 --> 00:30:38,880
(RUMBLING)

602
00:30:43,040 --> 00:30:45,160
(ROARING INTENSIFIES)

603
00:30:46,440 --> 00:30:48,120
(GROANING)

604
00:30:53,320 --> 00:30:54,400
Doctor?

605
00:30:57,800 --> 00:30:59,120
Doctor?

606
00:30:59,240 --> 00:31:01,120
They'd be here if they were coming,
where are they?

607
00:31:01,200 --> 00:31:03,280
There's no other way down, right?

608
00:31:04,400 --> 00:31:06,200
Hey! I'm talking to you.

609
00:31:06,280 --> 00:31:07,520
-There is.
-(FAINT HISSING)

610
00:31:07,600 --> 00:31:09,880
An old service elevator
near the mouth of the tunnel.

611
00:31:10,400 --> 00:31:12,080
CLARA: We should go.

612
00:31:12,920 --> 00:31:14,160
Oh, no.

613
00:31:15,600 --> 00:31:16,960
(RIPPLING)

614
00:31:20,640 --> 00:31:22,400
And there's another train coming.

615
00:31:22,480 --> 00:31:24,280
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLARING)

616
00:31:30,160 --> 00:31:32,160
(WHIRRING)

617
00:31:38,760 --> 00:31:40,200
(BRAKES SCREECHING)

618
00:31:44,640 --> 00:31:47,080
I don't know if you can still
hear me out there

619
00:31:47,160 --> 00:31:50,880
but the Tardis is now in siege mode.

620
00:31:50,960 --> 00:31:54,160
No way in, no way out.

621
00:31:55,400 --> 00:31:58,440
I managed to turn it on
just before the train hit.

622
00:31:59,320 --> 00:32:02,680
But there's not enough power
left now to turn it off.

623
00:32:05,080 --> 00:32:06,800
What's going on?

624
00:32:06,880 --> 00:32:08,160
Why the red light?

625
00:32:08,240 --> 00:32:10,040
MI5. We've got a, uh...

626
00:32:10,120 --> 00:32:11,840
Blockage. In the tunnel.

627
00:32:11,920 --> 00:32:14,280
Can we ram the...blockage?

628
00:32:14,360 --> 00:32:16,680
-The train's empty, isn't it?
-(FAINT RIPPLING)

629
00:32:16,760 --> 00:32:18,560
CONDUCTOR:
Yeah, it's out of service but...

630
00:32:18,640 --> 00:32:20,520
Well, you need someone
to hold the dead man's handle.

631
00:32:20,600 --> 00:32:23,840
Won't run without it. Is this official?

632
00:32:23,920 --> 00:32:25,760
Because I've always wanted
to ram something.

633
00:32:25,840 --> 00:32:28,360
Can we rig it to drive without that?
Send it in with no driver?

634
00:32:28,440 --> 00:32:30,600
-(STEAM HISSING)
-(ENGINE STARTING)

635
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:36,240
Rigsy!

636
00:32:44,360 --> 00:32:46,000
Uh, what are you doing?

637
00:32:46,080 --> 00:32:47,960
Look, I'm going to ram them,
buy you some time.

638
00:32:48,040 --> 00:32:49,720
-You'll die.
-Yeah, course I'll die.

639
00:32:49,800 --> 00:32:51,480
-Now, go!
-Well, why do you want to do that?

640
00:32:51,560 --> 00:32:53,680
Just go, okay? Let me do this.

641
00:32:54,400 --> 00:32:57,560
Okay, fine. Yeah.
And I'll always remember you.

642
00:32:57,640 --> 00:32:58,640
Fine. Yeah, great.

643
00:32:58,720 --> 00:33:00,240
'Cause I was just going to do this.

644
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:04,560
No driver required.
And I really like that hairband.

645
00:33:04,640 --> 00:33:06,360
But I suppose I'll just take it, will I?

646
00:33:06,440 --> 00:33:08,000
And every time I look at it,
I'll always remember

647
00:33:08,080 --> 00:33:09,520
the hero who died to save it.

648
00:33:12,680 --> 00:33:14,000
Come on.

649
00:33:14,080 --> 00:33:16,520
You're not getting off that lightly,
there's work that needs doing.

650
00:33:28,480 --> 00:33:29,480
(RIGSY GRUNTS)

651
00:33:30,800 --> 00:33:32,280
(CLARA GRUNTING)

652
00:33:32,360 --> 00:33:34,080
(CRASHING)

653
00:33:39,080 --> 00:33:40,680
I quite liked that hairband.

654
00:33:41,280 --> 00:33:43,160
(RIPPLING)

655
00:33:51,960 --> 00:33:53,840
RIGSY: What is it?

656
00:33:54,680 --> 00:33:56,560
I think it's the Tardis.

657
00:33:56,640 --> 00:33:58,320
(RIPPLING)

658
00:34:12,080 --> 00:34:13,840
CONDUCTOR:
They wear your skin?

659
00:34:13,920 --> 00:34:16,040
FENTON: I never thought
I'd say this, this is insane,

660
00:34:16,120 --> 00:34:18,120
but I think I preferred them
when they were flat.

661
00:34:18,200 --> 00:34:20,040
What do you mean, flat?

662
00:34:20,120 --> 00:34:21,320
Doctor?

663
00:34:21,400 --> 00:34:23,160
(RADIO STATIC)

664
00:34:25,040 --> 00:34:26,600
Doctor?

665
00:34:29,600 --> 00:34:31,320
What would you do now?

666
00:34:35,360 --> 00:34:38,080
No. What will I do now?

667
00:34:38,760 --> 00:34:41,240
Okay, okay, okay.

668
00:34:41,320 --> 00:34:44,160
Okay. The last thing the Doctor said

669
00:34:44,240 --> 00:34:46,880
was that the Tardis needed energy.

670
00:34:47,200 --> 00:34:50,360
He said if it gets energy,
he can beat them.

671
00:34:55,120 --> 00:34:56,840
No, no, no. What are you doing?

672
00:35:22,320 --> 00:35:23,400
(RATTLING)

673
00:35:23,480 --> 00:35:25,440
Leave her. She's lost it.

674
00:35:26,560 --> 00:35:28,360
-Are you okay?
-Yeah, are you?

675
00:35:28,440 --> 00:35:29,640
I think I will be. What's this?

676
00:35:29,720 --> 00:35:32,360
Come on, Graffiti Boy,
I've got a commission for you.

677
00:35:33,240 --> 00:35:34,920
-I'm flattered but I don't think this...
-Well, fine,

678
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:37,520
if you don't think you're up to it.

679
00:35:41,280 --> 00:35:42,640
What do you need, exactly?

680
00:36:04,800 --> 00:36:07,640
You're going to get us killed.
This plan's insane.

681
00:36:07,720 --> 00:36:10,760
You want to walk, walk.
You want to stay, then, shush!

682
00:36:10,920 --> 00:36:12,560
-CONDUCTOR: They're coming!
-(RIPPLING)

683
00:36:13,960 --> 00:36:15,840
(RIPPLING)

684
00:36:27,640 --> 00:36:29,560
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

685
00:36:33,440 --> 00:36:34,920
Life support failing.

686
00:36:36,720 --> 00:36:38,880
I don't know if you'll ever
hear this, Clara.

687
00:36:41,360 --> 00:36:44,560
I don't even know
if you're still alive out there.

688
00:36:44,640 --> 00:36:46,600
(CRACKLING)

689
00:36:47,680 --> 00:36:49,280
DOCTOR: But you were good!

690
00:36:55,040 --> 00:36:57,920
And you made a mighty fine Doctor.

691
00:37:05,640 --> 00:37:09,080
It's not working. You've killed us all.

692
00:37:09,160 --> 00:37:12,440
This is going to save us?
Pumping energy into the wall?

693
00:37:13,080 --> 00:37:16,320
No. Not into the wall,
through the wall.

694
00:37:17,880 --> 00:37:21,800
Rule number one of being the Doctor,
use your enemy's power against them.

695
00:37:21,880 --> 00:37:24,000
(CRACKLING CONTINUES)

696
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:35,240
CLARA: They can't restore three
dimensions to a door that never existed.

697
00:37:38,160 --> 00:37:39,640
(TARDIS POWERING UP)

698
00:37:44,280 --> 00:37:45,720
(COUGHING)

699
00:37:45,800 --> 00:37:46,800
(BEEPING)

700
00:37:49,400 --> 00:37:50,400
(FLICKING SWITCHES)

701
00:37:54,800 --> 00:37:56,400
(FAINT WHOOSHING)

702
00:38:00,560 --> 00:38:03,120
(WHOOSHING)

703
00:38:07,640 --> 00:38:09,200
It worked. (LAUGHS)

704
00:38:10,800 --> 00:38:12,200
They charged the Tardis.

705
00:38:13,000 --> 00:38:15,600
(PANTING) I tried to talk.
I want you to remember that.

706
00:38:15,680 --> 00:38:17,480
I tried to reach out.

707
00:38:17,880 --> 00:38:21,600
I tried to understand you but I think
that you understand us perfectly.

708
00:38:22,200 --> 00:38:24,400
(ON LOUDSPEAKER)
And I think that you just don't care.

709
00:38:24,480 --> 00:38:27,360
And I don't know
whether you are here to invade,

710
00:38:27,440 --> 00:38:30,040
infiltrate or just replace us.

711
00:38:30,120 --> 00:38:31,560
I don't suppose it really matters now.

712
00:38:31,640 --> 00:38:33,160
You are monsters!

713
00:38:33,240 --> 00:38:35,800
That is the role
you seem determined to play.

714
00:38:35,880 --> 00:38:39,160
So it seems that I must play mine!

715
00:38:41,320 --> 00:38:43,600
The man that stops the monsters.

716
00:38:45,440 --> 00:38:47,280
I'm sending you back
to your own dimension.

717
00:38:47,360 --> 00:38:50,280
Who knows? Some of you
may even survive the trip.

718
00:38:50,360 --> 00:38:52,320
And if you do, remember this.

719
00:38:52,560 --> 00:38:54,560
-You are not welcome here!
-(RIPPLING)

720
00:38:54,640 --> 00:38:58,520
This plane is protected!
I am the Doctor!

721
00:39:02,160 --> 00:39:04,480
And I name you the Boneless!

722
00:39:04,560 --> 00:39:06,000
(BOOMING)

723
00:39:19,280 --> 00:39:21,000
(WHOOSHING)

724
00:39:34,120 --> 00:39:35,720
(CONDUCTOR SIGHS DEEPLY)

725
00:39:35,800 --> 00:39:37,160
(CLARA CHUCKLES)

726
00:39:40,080 --> 00:39:41,280
Hi, Mum.

727
00:39:42,600 --> 00:39:45,400
It's me. Just listen.

728
00:39:45,520 --> 00:39:47,080
CLARA: You all right?
CONDUCTOR: I'm alive.

729
00:39:47,160 --> 00:39:50,240
And I've been inside that.
I think I'm up on the deal.

730
00:39:50,680 --> 00:39:52,000
Come here.

731
00:39:53,600 --> 00:39:54,800
Thank you.

732
00:39:59,800 --> 00:40:01,080
DOCTOR: You look chipper.

733
00:40:02,920 --> 00:40:05,760
-Do people still say "chipper"?
-Apparently.

734
00:40:06,440 --> 00:40:08,440
-You okay?
-I'm alive.

735
00:40:08,520 --> 00:40:09,840
And a lot of people died.

736
00:40:09,920 --> 00:40:11,200
FENTON: It's like a forest fire,
though, innit?

737
00:40:11,280 --> 00:40:15,080
The objective is to save the great
trees, not the brushwood. Am I right?

738
00:40:15,160 --> 00:40:17,280
It wasn't a fire, those weren't trees,
those were people.

739
00:40:17,360 --> 00:40:21,040
They were community-payback scumbags,
I wouldn't lose any sleep.

740
00:40:22,000 --> 00:40:24,040
-I bet you won't.
-Good to be alive, though.

741
00:40:24,120 --> 00:40:26,680
Thank you. Seriously, thank you.

742
00:40:27,160 --> 00:40:30,120
Yes, a lot of people died and
maybe the wrong people survived.

743
00:40:30,200 --> 00:40:33,680
-Yeah, but we saved the world, right?
-We did.

744
00:40:33,760 --> 00:40:35,960
-You did.
-Okay, so on balance...

745
00:40:36,640 --> 00:40:38,480
-On balance?
-Yeah, that's how you think, isn't it?

746
00:40:39,400 --> 00:40:41,280
Largely so other people don't have to.

747
00:40:41,360 --> 00:40:43,520
Yeah, well, I was you today.
I was the Doctor.

748
00:40:44,280 --> 00:40:47,440
And apparently, I was quite good at it.

749
00:40:48,160 --> 00:40:49,480
-You heard that, did you?
-Yeah.

750
00:40:49,560 --> 00:40:51,440
But the power was going off,
so I suppose you were delirious.

751
00:40:51,520 --> 00:40:53,320
You didn't know what you were saying.

752
00:40:53,400 --> 00:40:54,400
Yes.

753
00:40:57,320 --> 00:41:00,560
Ah! The return of the
fluorescent pudding brain!

754
00:41:00,960 --> 00:41:04,040
-You do realise he can hear you now?
-I know.

755
00:41:04,120 --> 00:41:05,560
Your last painting was so good,
it saved the world.

756
00:41:05,640 --> 00:41:07,560
I can't wait to see what you do next.

757
00:41:07,760 --> 00:41:09,120
(LAUGHS)

758
00:41:09,200 --> 00:41:10,560
It's not going to be easy.

759
00:41:11,080 --> 00:41:13,400
I've got a hairband to live up to.

760
00:41:14,320 --> 00:41:15,680
-Thanks.
-Come here.

761
00:41:31,120 --> 00:41:32,960
Admit it, I did well!

762
00:41:33,040 --> 00:41:34,440
(MOBILE RINGING)

763
00:41:34,520 --> 00:41:35,920
Is that PE?

764
00:41:37,560 --> 00:41:38,800
-Just say it.
-(DOCTOR COUGHS)

765
00:41:38,880 --> 00:41:40,440
Why can't you just say it?

766
00:41:41,280 --> 00:41:43,000
Why can't you just say I did good?

767
00:41:43,080 --> 00:41:44,760
-Talk to soldier-boy.
-It's not him.

768
00:41:45,240 --> 00:41:47,960
Come on! Why can't you say it?

769
00:41:48,640 --> 00:41:50,040
I was the Doctor and I was good.

770
00:41:50,120 --> 00:41:52,160
You were an exceptional Doctor, Clara.

771
00:41:52,240 --> 00:41:53,240
Thank you.

772
00:41:53,320 --> 00:41:56,200
Goodness had nothing to do with it.

773
00:42:08,680 --> 00:42:11,680
Clara. My Clara.

774
00:42:12,360 --> 00:42:14,480
I have chosen well.

775
00:42:22,600 --> 00:42:24,160
I think it's lovely.

776
00:42:24,880 --> 00:42:25,920
(GROWLING)

777
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:27,520
COMPUTER:
You have reached your destination.

778
00:42:27,600 --> 00:42:29,320
No, we haven't. We're supposed to be
in the middle of London.

779
00:42:29,400 --> 00:42:31,400
-You have reached your destination.
-(WOLF HOWLING)

780
00:42:31,480 --> 00:42:33,560
DOCTOR: Oh, stop staying that!

781
00:42:33,640 --> 00:42:35,600
GIRL: She's only saying it
because it's true.

782
00:42:36,400 --> 00:42:38,320
We are in the middle of London.

783
00:42:38,960 --> 00:42:41,240
DOCTOR: We are in
the middle of a forest.

784
00:42:41,560 --> 00:42:43,160
Come on, team, let's do this!

785
00:42:43,240 --> 00:42:46,040
-We will, if you stop calling us a team.
-(LOW GROWLING)

786
00:42:46,120 --> 00:42:48,120
-(PANTING)
-(ROARING)

787
00:42:49,480 --> 00:42:51,280
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

